value.value: The phase of the blood feeding from first appearance of blood in the fascicle to the start of withdrawal.
The phase of the blood feeding from first straightening of the forelegs to complete removal of the stylets from the skin.
A meal acquired from two or more hosts, which may have been of the same species (single-species mixed meal) or different species (multi-species mixed meal).
A blood meal resulting from a single feed. It may be complete or, as a result of interruption, incomplete.
A second, third or yet further blood meal acquired in a single gonotrophic cycle through supplementary feeding.
During a single gonotrophic cycle, the female takes more than one blood meal. Multiple feeding involves multiple host contacts.
Acquisition of a blood meal in two or more parts, the mosquito having left its host while only partly fed, due to disturbance, and having resumed feeding soon afterwards on the same or another host.

Acquisition of additional blood meals after the first during a single gonotrophic cycle, independently of interruption due to disturbance, the feedings being separated by intervals of several hours to a day or more.

label.value: regulation of food intake in adults

value.value: The control of feeding and distribution of food within the gut by integrated responses of the peripheral sensilla, central nervous system and, probably, the stomatogastric system. Feeding generally terminates in response to mechanical stimulation caused by swelling of the gut.
The regulation of the sugar intake in mosquitoes using chemosensilla and sugar receptors.
When mosquitoes drink, two control processes are involved: one regulates the destination of the fluid the other regulates the volume that is imbibed.

Female mosquitoes gorge on blood when it is applied by capillary tube to the unsheathed fascicle or offered through an artificial membrane. Whether stimulation of just the larbal sensilla with blood is sufficient to induce drinking is not known, but certainly stimulation of both larbal and cibarial sensilla is sufficient.

The sequence of behaviour patterns exhibited by mosquitoes responding to hosts over a distance. Host-seeking behaviour terminates once feeding is initiated and blood ingestion begins. For each species, host-finding activity is exhibited during one or more periods in the diel.
Activation is the first response to host cues; it is the initial response in a sequence of behaviours that ends with arrival at the host.

definition.value: Mosquitoes can be activated by host cues at any time. Un-fed, resting females of some species will attack at any hour if disturbed in their shelters by intrusion of a host or stimulated by odour from a nearby host. Such opportunistic biting has been observed in nocturnal mosquitoes disturbed by day. The activation step is readily observed in the laboratory but has seldom been described from the field.

value.value: The navigation of the mosquitoes towards potential hosts through their responses to a variety of cues emanating from them. Some host cues are chemical and others are physical.
The resting of females in their host's proximity after they had approached them and before making a final approach and feeding.

definition.value: This phenomenon is been described in some members of the Leucosphyrus Subgroup, in Anopheles dirus, in Anopheles gambie, Anopheles arabiensis, Culex quinquefasciatus.

value.value: The final stage of host finding; it comprises four steps.

definition.value: This phase of host finding may follow a long-range approach or, if arrival of a host activates a resting mosquito, it may start immediately after activation. The short-range approach to the host is assumed to start when cues other than host odour are first perceived by the mosquito.

value.value: The first step of short-range approach, alighting and exploration; from the perception of cues by the mosquito to the approach of the host.

definition.value: Is assumed to start when cues other than host odour are first perceived by the mosquito.

label.value: descent to the body surface and alighting

value.value: The second step of the short-range approach, alighting and exploration.

definition.value: Except in total darkness, visual responces may govern the final stage of flight into the presence of a potential host, but additional stimuli may be required before the mosquito alights on the host.

label.value: exploration and examination of the body surface

value.value: In this step the mosquito walks over the body, rapidly tapping the surface with its labella, and it may fly from one body region to another in order to find a region of vascularized skin into which it can drive its stylets.
The digestion of blood and nectar. The midgut is the principal organ of digestion, but dissaccharides ingested in nectar are at least partly hydrolysed in the crop by a salivary enzyme.
The regulation of enzyme synthesis by the presence of blood in the midgut or not.

label.value: absorption of the products of digestion

value.value: For the female: digestion of blood proteins yields amino acids which are reconstituted in the mosquito's fat body as proteinaceous yolk. This is important for oogenesis. For both sexes: Plant juices provide an important energy source. They are the only food sources for males.
The formation of a membrane which is deposited around the ingested blood mass.
The formation of vitellogenin in the fat body. It is synthesized first as precursors which undergo proteolytic cleavage into two or more subunits.

definition.value: Vitellogenin was first detected by immunofluorescence onr hour after feeding, and vitellogenin seretion granules were observed at the cell membrane within three hours.

value.value: The act of sexual intercourse, during which the genitalia are engaged and the aedeagus inserted, and semen is passed to the female. It usually lasts a few seconds.

definition.value: In some species the process of copulation may last for many minutes.

value.value: Developing oocytes accumulate proteinaceous yolk by internalizing large amounts of circulating vitellogenin.
The process occurring when a male first responds to a female, seizing her and establishing genital contact.
The rapid production of urine containing principally water and salts.
The release of the unmodified secretion of the Malpighiann tubules.
The tubular fluid is expelled as urine. Tubular fluids are the unmodified secretion of the Malpighian tubules.
The tubular fluid enters the pylorus from where some may be move forwards for resorption in the midgut.
The portion of the tubular fluid that is not absorbed in the hindgut and is moved posteriorly to the rectum where it is modified producing urine.
During the first day after feeding, deamination of amino acids produces excess nitrogen which is voided in the form of low molecular weight nitrogenous metabolites.
During a single gonotrophic cycle, the female takes only one blood meal.
The fluid intake due to the activity of the cibarial and pharyngeal pumps.
The separation of the labellar lobes following stimulation by sugar of sensilla on the outer surface of the labella.
The searching movements made with the proboscis when the tarsi are stimulated by sugar.
The union of male and female gametes and formation of a zygote in anopheline vectors.
The major pathway by which carbohydrates are degraded in insects for energy release.
The energy contained within fatty acid molecules is made available by b-oxidation of the fatty acid.
The steps of a second, third or yet further meal acquired in a single gonotrophic cycle.
The feeding on sugar.
The process of energy absorption from a physical stimulus by a sensillum and its transmission to sensory neurons.
Behaviour displayed by mosquitoes that feed on a few host species only, while in habitats in which a wide range of potential hosts is present.

In both culicines and anophelines, peritrophic membrane that is secreted in the enterior midgut slowly retracts and twists, forming a plug between the anterior medgut and stomach. A similar plug forms between the stomach and hindgut.
A change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a toxin stimulus.

label.value: secretion of peritrophic matrix in adults

value.value: All midgut columnal cells secrete the substance of the membrane which is deposited around the ingested blood mass.

label.value: secretion of peritrophic matrix in larvae

value.value: The membrane is secreted by a narrow band of cells at the anterior end of the mindgut and is formed as a continuous tube.
Is the feeding mode most common used by mosquito larvae.
